XThis YAML defines two Kubernetes Services that expose Pods inside the cluster.
Service 1: hp-communication-app-service
YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: hp-communication-app-service
  namespace: hp-communication
spec:
  type: ClusterIP
  ports:
  - port: 80
    targetPort: http
    protocol: TCP
  selector:
    app: hp-communication-app
What it does:
Creates a Service named hp-communication-app-service.
Exists in namespace hp-communication.
Uses ClusterIP, meaning it is only reachable from within the Kubernetes cluster.
Exposes port 80.
Forwards traffic to Pod port named http.
Selects Pods with:
YAML
labels:
  app: hp-communication-app
Service 2: hp-communication-ui-service
YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: hp-communication-ui-service
  namespace: hp-communication
spec:
  type: ClusterIP
  ports:
  - port: 80
    targetPort: http
    protocol: TCP
  selector:
    app: hp-communication-ui
What it does:
Creates a Service named hp-communication-ui-service.
Internal-only (ClusterIP).
Exposes port 80.
Routes traffic to Pods labeled:
YAML
labels:
  app: hp-communication-ui
Sends requests to the container port named http.
Important requirement
For targetPort: http to work, the selected Pods must define a container port named http, for example:
YAML
containers:
- name: app
  image: hp/app:latest
  ports:
  - name: http
    containerPort: 8080
If the Pods instead have:
YAML
ports:
- containerPort: 8080
without the name: http, the Service will fail to route traffic correctly.
In that case use:
YAML
targetPort: 8080
instead of:
YAML
targetPort: http
Resulting DNS names inside the cluster
Pods can reach these services via:
Plain text
hp-communication-app-service.hp-communication.svc.cluster.local
and
Plain text
hp-communication-ui-service.hp-communication.svc.cluster.local
or simply:
Plain text
http://hp-communication-app-service
http://hp-communication-ui-service
when running in the same namespace.
This configuration looks normal for a setup where:
hp-communication-ui = frontend/UI
hp-communication-app = backend/API
with both accessible only within the cluster until an Ingress or LoadBalancer is added.
This section explains how GitHub aggregates usage metrics for GitHub Actions.
What is included?
GitHub counts:
Workflow runs that actually executed.
Minutes consumed by those runs.
GitHub does not count:
Skipped workflow runs.
Runs that consumed 0 minutes.
All dates are calculated using UTC (Coordinated Universal Time).
Available time ranges
Period
What it shows
Current week (Mon–Sun)
From Monday of the current week up to today
Current month
From the 1st day of the current month up to today
Last month
Entire previous calendar month
Last 30 days
Rolling 30-day window ending today
Last 90 days
Rolling 90-day window ending today
Last year
Aggregated data for the previous 12 months
Custom
User-selected range, up to 100 days long and within the last year
Example
Suppose today is June 7, 2026 (UTC):
Current week → June 1–7, 2026
Current month → June 1–7, 2026
Last month → May 1–31, 2026
Last 30 days → May 8–June 7, 2026
Last 90 days → March 10–June 7, 2026
Last year → June 2025–June 2026 aggregated monthly
Why aggregation matters
The metrics page helps repository and organization administrators:
Track workflow usage trends.
Monitor billed GitHub Actions minutes.
Identify repositories consuming the most runner time.
Analyze usage over specific periods for budgeting and optimization.
For organizations using GitHub Actions heavily, these reports can help determine whether self-hosted runners or workflow optimizations might reduce costs and execution time.
GitHub Actions metrics aggregation

The time period selection feature allows you to view GitHub Actions metrics over predefined periods, as detailed in the following table. These metrics exclude skipped runs and those that use zero minutes. Data is presented using Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) days.
Period
Description
Current week (Mon-Sun)
Data from Monday through the current day when the page is viewed.
Current month
Data from the first of the month to the current day when the page is viewed.
Last month
Data from the first day to the last day of the previous month.
Last 30 days
Data from the last 30 days to when the page is viewed.
Last 90 days
Data from the last 90 days to when the page is viewed.
Last year
Data aggregated for the last 12 months.
Custom
Data from a custom date range. The range can be up to 100 days including the start and end dates and go back as far as one year.
